				<p><p>Simplicity, i guess. A USB implementation (chips and driver software) is usually more complex than good ol' RS232, which can even be found in many 8-bit microcontrollers. While USB has many protocol mechanisms and is designed to deal with many participants over a bus, a RS232 connection doesn't have any of that. Instead, it's the "rawest" form possible of sending bytes over a wire.</p>

<p>Although Arduino and increasing spread of USB-to-serial adapters show promise that USB will eventually become as dominant as RS232 used to be.</p>
