				<p><p>I think the biggest reason that RS232 has stayed around is the simplicity in implementing common use-cases in embedded hardware - like sending a sequence ASCII bytes between two devices for control. The use-cases for sending information at the much higher speeds available with USB are not worth the trade-off in complexity caused by implementing <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Serial_Bus#Signaling">the USB protocol's signalling</a>.</p>

<p>As the requirements for higher speeds appear, I wouldn't be surprised if <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RS-485">RS-485</a> became more common with it's very simple physical interface and high (up to 10Mb/s) data rates.</p>
</p><br>
